0":"1340","1281":"1281","Abt 1349":"about 1349","1290":"1290","Bottisham, Cambridgeshire, England":"Bottisham, Cambridgeshire, England","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mallett","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English female personal name <i>Malot</i>, more rarely <i>Malet</i>, a pet form of   Mall  , <i>Mald</i> (i.e. Maud, Matilda) + the diminutive suffix <i>-ot</i> or <i>-et</i>. In post-medieval forms of the surname final <i>-ot</i> was generally altered to <i>-et(t)</i>. Though there are alternative Norman origins (see below), this is the usual source of the English surname.","English: of Norman origin, a nickname from Old French <i>maillet</i> ‘hammer’ (see   Maillet  , compare   Mallet   4), used as a battle weapon. Robert Malet, lord of the Honour of Eye (Suffolk) in 1086, was the son of William Malet of Graville-Sainte-Honorine (Seine-Maritime). The latter is referred to as Gulielmo agnomine <i>Mal(l)eto</i> ‘William, surnamed Mal(l)et’ in the late 11th-century Gesta Guillelmi of William of Poitiers and the early 12th-century Historia Ecclesia of Orderic Vitalis. According to tradition, this surname arose because of William's reputation for bludgeoning his enemies in battle <i>(cum) malleo</i> ‘with the hammer’. The story may be true or it may have been invented to explain the name, in which case see 3 below for an alternative etymology.","English: of Norman origin, from the Old French personal name <i>Malet</i>, a pet form of   Malo  . Compare   Mallet   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Mall","meanings":["English: from the medieval female personal name <i>Mall</i>, a common form of <i>Mald</i> or <i>Maud</i>. See also   Maude   and   Moll  . It had several pet forms; see   Malin  ,   Malkin  , and   Mallet  .","Indian (northern states): from Sanskrit <i>malla</i> ‘strongman, wrestler’."]},{"name":"Maillet","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Yvon, Emile, Ulysse, Alphee, Andre, Jean-Paul, Laurent, Normand, Alban, Alcide, Allain, Antoine.","French:","from Old French <i>maillet</i> ‘mallet’, used as a metonymic occupational name for someone who worked with such an implement, e.g. a smith, or as a nickname for a fearsome warrior (see English   Mallett   2)."]},{"name":"Maillot","meanings":["(2010: NA)","French:","from Old French <i>maillot</i> ‘big mallet’, used as a metonymic occupational name for someone who worked with such an implement, e.g. a smith, and perhaps also as a nickname for a fearsome warrior (see English   Mallett   2). This is the usual form of the surname in France (it is, however, most frequent in Réunion), while in North America it is normally spelled   Mailhot  ."]}]},{"name":"Dionysia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Denise ;   see  Dennis .  This form was in use in northern England from the 14th to the 17th century; the short form  <b>Dye</b>  is the source of the surname <i>Dyson</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Dionysia Mallett was born about 1320, in Bottisham, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, William Mallett, was 31 and her mother, Mrs William Mallett, was 40. She married William Alington about 1349, in Bottisham, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She was buried in Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1320–":"umbes 1320–Surnud","1310–Male":"1310–Surnud","1320–Female":"1320–Surnud","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1365–1446":"1365–1446","1290–Male":"1290–Surnud","1281–Female":"1281–Surnud","1446":"1446","Abt 1320":"umbes 1320","1365":"1365","1310":"1310","1320":"1320","1340":"1340","1281":"1281","Abt 1349":"umbes 1349","1290":"1290","Bottisham, Cambridgeshire, England":"Bottisham, Cambridgeshire, England","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshi